Step 1: Find the area of the parallelogram using the cross product. The cross product of two vectors $\bold{v}$ and $\bold{w}$ is given by $\bold{v} \times \bold{w} = \begin{vmatrix} \bold{i} & \bold{j} & \bold{k} \\ 5 & -3 & 0 \\ 11 & -2 & 0 \end{vmatrix}$. Expanding the determinant, we get $\bold{v} \times \bold{w} = \bold{i}(-3 \cdot 0 - 0 \cdot -2) - \bold{j}(5 \cdot 0 - 0 \cdot 11) + \bold{k}(5 \cdot -2 - (-3) \cdot 11)$. Simplifying, we get $\bold{v} \times \bold{w} = \bold{i}(0) - \bold{j}(0) + \bold{k}(-10 + 33)$. So, $\bold{v} \times \bold{w} = \bold{k}(23)$. The magnitude of the cross product is the area of the parallelogram. So, the area of the parallelogram is $|\bold{v} \times \bold{w}| = |23| = 23$.

Answer:
\boxed{23}
